				<div class="heading">
				Lay Summary
				</div><!--heading-->

<!--PARAGRAPH WITH HEADER-->	
<a name=""></a>
<p>
<h1 class="suborange">Motivation</h1>
Bacteria need to obtain nitrogen from their environment in order to survive and proliferate. Currently, little is known about the bacterial response to nitrogen starvation. Recent experimental work suggests some bacteria (including <i>M.smegmatis</i>) may be storing nitrogen in times of plenty, as they can continue to grow after it is exhausted from their medium. One possibility is that nitrogen is being stored in the form of specialised proteins, and this is what we want to investigate.
</p>

<p>
<h1 class="suborange">Methods</h1>
We take protein sequences from proteins we already know to store nitrogen in plants, animals and fungi, and calculate a wide range things about them using only the amino acid sequence. We then teach an artificial intelligence program called a random forest what that the group of storage proteins looks like from the features, and what an equivalent group of non-storage proteins looks like. The result is a classification program, which makes a prediction whether unseen proteins are storage proteins or not, and we apply it to the complete set of proteins from the bacterium <i>M.smegmatis</i>, to try to identify possible storage protein candidates.
</p>
<p>
<h1 class="suborange">Results</h1>
The classifier was 90% accurate at discriminating previously-known storage proteins and non-storage proteins, and is not biased to any particular subset of proteins in the group we taught it with. 7 storage protein candidates were identified at a precision level of 99% from the <i>M.smegmatis</i> protein set and are worthy of further investigation.
</p>
<p>
<h1 class="suborange">Conclusion</h1>
The random forest approach is fast and highly effective at discriminating proteins based on sequence-based properties, and could be easily applied to any similar investigation. Further work with the candidates identified in this project could help develop our understanding of nitrogen stress responses in bacteria. There are wider ramifications in the field of medicine where, if their existence is confirmed, bacterial nitrogen storage proteins could make potential antibiotic drug targets. This is a very important area of research due to the rise of antibiotic-resistant strains such as MRSA.
		<br /><br /><br />
